What are some things you notice in the ggpairs output? Response: - x, y and z are almost perfectly correlated to each other (means diamonds always come in same shapes) - price is also quite strongly correlated to x, y, z (ie volume of diamond) - carat is strongly correlated to price and x, y, z (which we expected) - depth shows no impact on price (reject feature for price prediction) - We already saw the weird inverse relation of color and clarity to price (against intuition) - Nothing substantial stands out wrt. to cut, but we cannot eliminate it just yet - Hypothesize that since weight is a function of volume, price may be related to cube of carat

The Demand of Diamonds

Notes: - Maybe the case that in the smaller diamonds, there is less affluent buyers, so this is price sensitive. This makes the variation of price for sub-carat diamonds not show much variation - For larger sizes, there is not much demand, and demand is from affluent people. So, possibly much wider variation in prices for weight > 1 carat

  • May be instrumental to transform the price variable using log http://www.r-statistics.com/2013/05/log-transformations-for-skewed-and-wide-distributions-from-practical-data-science-with-r/
library(gridExtra)
## Loading required package: grid
plot1 <- qplot(data = subset(diamonds, price > 0) , x= price, color = 'black', fill = I('#ff88aa'), binwidth = 100) + 
  ggtitle('Price')

# Note, in log plot, you have to pick bin width after the transformation
plot2 <- qplot(data = subset(diamonds, price > 0), x = price, color = 'black', fill = I('#aa88ff'), binwidth = 0.01) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  ggtitle('Price (log10)') 

grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, ncol = 1)
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): position_stack requires constant width:
## output may be incorrect

Notes: - - Price distribution is +vely skewed with long tail. Hence, log10 transformation should help convert to near normal - Note that for applying LR, we only require inputs to be approx normal, not the the output itself - Money is also multiplicative - year on year inflation, path dependent (rich become richer) etc - For monetary variables, which are highly skewed and have orders of magnitude variance, it is useful to apply log transformation - This also helps data models which don’t do well when there is orders of magnitude difference Post, transformation, we see it is bimodal, but closer to normal, so we will apply LR on log10(y) instead of y

Connecting Demand and Price Distributions

Notes: - First peak for price senstive customers - Second peak is for affluent customers. Beyond a point, they also don’t think its worth it apparently

Create a new function to transform the carat variable

Notes: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z1wB1rHAYzQ&list=PLOU2XLYxmsIK9qQfztXeybpHvru-TrqAP http://blog.ggplot2.org/post/25938265813/defining-a-new-transformation-for-ggplot2-scales

Note: Write a general function called ‘cuberoot_trans()’ that returns the cube root of input param

cuberoot_trans = function() trans_new('cuberoot', transform = function(x) x^(1/3),
                                      inverse = function(x) x^(3))

Use the cuberoot_trans function

ggplot(aes(carat, price), data = diamonds) + 
  geom_point(color = 'red', alpha = 1/5) +
#  scale_x_continuous(trans = cuberoot_trans()) +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = cuberoot_trans(), limits = c(0.2, 3),
                     breaks = c(0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 3)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(trans = log10_trans(), limits = c(350, 15000),
                     breaks = c(350, 1000, 5000, 10000, 15000)) +
  ggtitle('Price (log10) by Cube-Root of Carat')

Linear Models in R

Notes: use lm(output ~ input_func) to perform linear regression

Response: - Use lm(log(price) ~ carat^(1/3)) based on our plot

Building the Linear Model

Notes: http://data.princeton.edu/R/linearModels.html Interpreting Regression Coefficients in R - http://www.r-bloggers.com/interpreting-regression-coefficient-in-r/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+RBloggers+%28R+bloggers%29 Interpreting Regression Coefficients on the Analysis Factor blog http://www.theanalysisfactor.com/interpreting-regression-coefficients/ Fitting and Interpreting Linear Models by yhat http://blog.yhathq.com/posts/r-lm-summary.html Another Explanation of Factor Coefficients in Linear Models on Stats StackExchange http://stats.stackexchange.com/a/24256

m1 <- lm(I(log(price)) ~ I(carat^(1/3)), data = diamonds)
m2 <- update(m1, ~ . + carat)
m3 <- update(m2, ~ . + cut)
m4 <- update(m3, ~ . + color)
m5 <- update(m4, ~ . + clarity)
mtable(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5)

Building a Model Using the Big Diamonds Data Set

Notes: Only consider diamonds that are GIA certified and price < 10000

diamondsBigSample <- subset(diamondsbig, cert == "GIA" & !is.na(price) & price <= 10000) 
m1 <- lm(I(log10(price)) ~ I(carat^(1/3)), data = diamondsBigSample)
m2 <- update(m1, ~ . + carat)
m3 <- update(m2, ~ . + cut)
m4 <- update(m3, ~ . + color)
m5 <- update(m4, ~ . + clarity)
mtable(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5)

Price Prediction using the Linear Model

Example Diamond from BlueNile: Round 1.00 Very Good I VS1 $5,601

#Be sure youâve loaded the library memisc and have m5 saved as an object in your workspace.
thisDiamond <- data.frame(carat = 1.00, cut = "V.Good",
                         color = "I", clarity="VS1")
modelEstimate <- predict(m5, newdata = thisDiamond,
                        interval="prediction", level = .95)

priceEst <- 10^modelEstimate
priceEst
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 5040.617 3730.418 6810.984

Evaluate how well the model predicts the BlueNile diamond’s price. Think about the fitted point estimate as well as the 95% CI.
